-- Self-Consistency of CredTT at Credence < 1
--
-- NOTE: This file DEMONSTRATES the proof checker syntax.
-- The actual metatheory is formalized in agda/CredTT/Consistency.agda
--
-- LITERATURE:
-- - LFIs: da Costa (1974), Carnielli-Coniglio (2016)
-- - Graded consistency: Pavelka-style fuzzy theories
--
-- Goedel's Second Incompleteness Theorem:
--   If T contains PA and T is consistent, then T cannot prove Con(T)
--
-- CredTT approach: graded consistency
--   We can prove Con(CredTT) @ c for c < 1
--   This doesn't trigger Goedel's obstruction
--
-- Key insight: Goedel's proof assumes binary provability
-- With graded provability, the argument breaks down

-- Consistency means "false is not provable at credence 1"
encode Con_CredTT = Not_Prov_False

-- We can reason about consistency at a lower credence
-- This is honest: we're fairly confident, not absolutely certain

-- Assume CredTT is sound (provable things are true)
postulate sound : Soundness 〔 1 〕

-- From soundness, we can derive consistency at credence c < 1
-- The credence reflects epistemic uncertainty about our own system
derive con_at_c : Con_CredTT 〔 c 〕 from sound by reflection

-- The fixpoint analysis shows why this works:
-- Goedel's G = "G is unprovable at credence 1"
-- In CredTT: G @ 1/2 (resolved, not undecidable)
-- So the self-referential loop has a stable solution

-- We can assert graded consistency
provable graded_con : Con_CredTT 〔 c 〕

-- What we CANNOT prove: Con(CredTT) @ 1
-- That would still trigger Goedel's obstruction
-- This is appropriate: absolute certainty about self-consistency
-- is indeed impossible for sufficiently strong systems

-- The graded version is philosophically honest:
-- - We believe CredTT is consistent
-- - We cannot be absolutely certain (Goedel)
-- - But we can quantify our confidence: credence c < 1
-- - This is more informative than classical "undecidable"

-- Self-referential consistency at the meta-level
-- fixpoint con_c = ... (the credence at which we can assert consistency)
-- The solution depends on the strength of the system
-- For CredTT, we expect c to be high (close to 1) but < 1
